<TEXT>
<P>
 THE CABIN: Reminiscence and Diversions by David Mahmet (Vintage: $10; 157 pp.) 
. Mahmet's episodic memoirs resemble a succession of scenes illuminated by an 
erratic strobe light: A single moment appears in harsh focus, then vanishes. A 
mundane dining room table triggers memories of his parents' emotional 
grandstanding and how they tyrannized his sister; a pleasant house in Vermont 
leads to speculations about the existence of neighborhood ghosts. The title 
essay is an affectionate portrait of the Pulitzer Prize winner's cozily 
disordered sanctum sanctorum. 
</P>
