RAMOS ON POLANCO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * I was shocked by George Ramos' criticism of Assemblyman Richard Polanco 
(D-Los Angeles) on what appear to be nakedly racist grounds (Feb. 28). 
</P>
<P>
 Ramos condemns Polanco for supporting his aide, Bill Mabie, for an Assembly 
seat held by a Chicano.Polanco says he talked to several qualified Latinos 
about the race, and all turned him down. Polanco then said that in his opinion 
Mabie was the best candidate for the job, and that the voters would eventually 
decide. 
</P>
<P>
 Ramos' response to what sounds like an elementary lesson in how the democratic 
process should work? "I don't buy Polanco's arguments. . . . What about helping 
your own kind. . . .?" 
</P>
<P>
 Apparently to Ramos "your own kind" is defined by the narrow bounds of race. 
Political philosophy and qualifications to serve should be subordinated to 
ethnicity. Based on that kind of thinking, someone like Rep. Xavier Becerra 
(D-Los Angeles), who represents a district where the vast majority of 
registered voters are not Latino, would not be elected, and Los Angeles will 
proceed down the path to becoming a mini-Bosnia, where ethnic background 
defines everything. 
</P>
<P>
 DALE N. FLANAGAN 
