<TEXT>
<P>
 JONES ALONE: Rickie Lee Jones fans got a treat when the singer previewed her 
first-ever solo acoustic tour recently with an informal show at the Troubadour. 
And there was a bonus: Lyle Lovett joined in on harmonies for three songs, 
including an unreleased Jones number.Bassist extraordinaire Rob Wasserman also 
made a guest appearance. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones seemed inspired by the close quarters of the club, joking with audience 
members who were shouting requests between songs, but commanding hushed 
attention during them. With Jones mostly alone at just a piano or acoustic 
guitar, her songs lost the musical complexity of their full-band arrangements, 
but gained in intimacy. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wanted to create something of a more secluded environment on stage," Jones 
told Pop Eye. In keeping with that, Jones will stick to small theaters on the 
tour, which starts Tuesday in Berkeley. A Los Angeles date is expected in 
April. Robert Levine 
</P>
