<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH CAROLINA KEEPS KENTUCKY FROM CLINCHING SEC EASTERN TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Emmett Hall stood alone in victory after being left alone under the basket for 
the winning basket. 
</P>
<P>
 Hall's layup from the right side with three seconds to go gave South Carolina 
a 75-74 victory over No. 7 Kentucky on Saturday, preventing the Wildcats from 
clinching the Southeastern Conference Eastern Division title. 
</P>
<P>
 Afterward, Hall jumped atop a chair and stretched out his arms to relish the 
Gamecocks' victory. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just remember thinking, 'The game is over,' " Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
 Hall, a senior, finished with 20 points and 13 rebounds and Donnie Mathews had 
all 14 of his points in the second half for South Carolina (8-18, 4-12), which 
beat a ranked team for the first time since defeating Temple on Dec. 8, 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 Rodrick Rhodes had 24 points to lead Kentucky (23-6, 12-4), which saw its 
five-game winning streak end. 
</P>
<P>
 The Wildcats shot only 38.6% and were held to their second-lowest point total 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "We didn't play as well as we were capable of, but still they played great 
basketball," said Travis Ford, held to six points for Kentucky. "I just didn't 
lead this team like I should have." 
</P>
</TEXT>
