<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN WILLIAMS; NOVELIST WON NATIONAL BOOK AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 John Williams, 71, an acclaimed novelist and poet who won the National Book 
Award in 1973.His novel "Augustus," a tale of the Roman golden age, won the 
National Book Award. Other works include "Nothing but the Night," published in 
1948; "Stoner" in 1965, and "Butcher's Crossing" in 1960. Williams also 
published two books of verse, "The Necessary Lie" and "The Broken Landscape," 
and edited the volume "English Renaissance Poetry," a classic text in 
Renaissance scholarship. He founded the Denver Quarterly magazine and taught at 
the University of Denver for 30 years. In Fayetteville, Ark., on Thursday of 
respiratory complications. 
</P>
