<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIDE TRIPS; SKY ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Anna Scotti 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Kites are bright, fluid bits of color in the sky, and colorful kites from 
every corner of the earth have been assembled at the World Kite Museum and Hall 
of Fame in Long Beach, Wash., for an exhibition called "Tethered Art." European 
and Asian kites as well as contemporary and antique American ones are on 
display through June 30.The 5-year-old museum also maintains a permanent show 
of nearly 1,000 kites from around the world, as well as books, videos and 
photographs. 
</P>
<P>
 World Kite Museum and Hall of Fame, 3rd Street North, Long Beach, Wash., (206) 
642-4020. Open 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. on weekends only until June 1, then open 
through the summer 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. Admission: $1 for adults, 50 cents 
for children and seniors and $3 for families. Anna Scotti 
</P>
</TEXT>
