<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRENSHAW WINS CITY 4-A CROWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Crenshaw High, The Times' No. 2-rated team, might not have played its best 
game of the season, but the Cougars still had enough to win their second 
consecutive City 4-A Division boys' basketball championship with a 72-53 
victory over Dorsey late Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Before an estimated crowd of 6,500 at the Sports Arena, Crenshaw Coach Willie 
West won his record-setting 13th City title.The Cougars, who have won five 
State titles, also defeated Dorsey in last year's championship game. 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw (25-2), which averaged 100.6 points a game this season, was led by 
California-bound forward Tremaine Fowlkes, who had 18 points, 16 rebounds and 
five blocked shots. 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw advances into the State Southern Regional tournament at the Anaheim 
Arena next Saturday. LONNIE WHITE 
</P>
</TEXT>
