<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIMPLE ENGLISH? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 How can you, in good conscience, print a letter quoting "Prof. Higgins" as an 
authority on relations between the sexes? (Feb. 13). Using this example, I 
suppose that if someone complained of a racist remark, a letter from the Klan 
would have to be printed to offer the "opposing view"? And yes, my lady denotes 
ownership, as my lady companion or my lady friend would not. Come on, it's 
simple English! 
</P>
<P>
 LAHNEEN GALLO 
</P>
<P>
 Rialto 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA030694-0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 020352 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
March 6, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Travel; Part L; Page 24; Column 2; Travel Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
99 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DON'T MISS MIDDLE EAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regarding the Feb. 13 issue on travel in the Middle East: 
</P>
<P>
 I am a mature woman who has traveled to Turkey, Syria, Jordan, Egypt and 
Israel during the last 10 years.English is my only language and I am somewhat 
shy, but usually travel alone or with another woman. Public transportation, 
inexpensive lodgings and a flexible agenda are typical of my trips. 
</P>
<P>
 I found Middle Eastern people friendly and helpful well beyond my 
expectations. I was respected and well cared for. I recommend travel in that 
part of the world -- it is neither daunting nor unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
 SYDNEY SIEMENS 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Barbara 
</P>
</TEXT>
